Name.creator: Blaney, Harry French,  $d 1892-1976
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. $b Library Special Collections
Title: Harry French Blaney Papers, 1919-1970
Description.note: Harry French Blaney was a civil engineer who worked for the U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA) (1917-1962), was a research associate in the Department of Irrigation Research and Soil Science at UCLA (1962-1965) and served in the Department of Engineering and Water Resource Center (1965-1973). He authored many publications on the consumptive use of water, irrigation, evaporation and water supply.
Description.abstract: Blaney was born in Los Angeles, California, July 19, 1892; BS, civil engineering, UC Berkeley, 1915; spent most of career working for U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA), 1917-62; research associate, Department of Irrigation Research and Soil Science, UCLA, 1962-65; served in Department of Engineering and Water Resource Center, 1965-73; author of many publications on consumptive use of water, irrigation, evaporation, and water supply; died in 1976.

Title: Two men in a field in an area near the flood following the failure of the Saint Francis Dam, Santa Clara River Valley (Calif.), 1928
Description.caption: Text from negative sleeve: St. Francis Dam. 3-18-28.
Description.note: The St. Francis Dam was a 200-foot high concrete gravity-arch dam built between 1924 and 1926 in St. Francisquito Canyon (near present-day Castaic and Santa Clarita). The dam collapsed on March 12, 1928 at two and a half minutes before midnight. The resulting flood killed more than 600 residents plus an unknown number of itinerant farm workers camped in San Francisquito Canyon, making it the 2nd greatest loss of life in California after the 1906 San Francisco earthquake. It is considered the worst American civil engineering failure in the 20th century.

Title: View of the remaining center portion of the St. Francis Dam after its disastrous collapse, San Francisquito Canyon (Calif.), 1928
Description.caption: Text from the negative sleeve St. Francis Dam and Santa Clara Valley. St. Francis Dam Flood Area. [In an envelope from the:] United States Department of Agriculture, Soil Conservation Service, Bureau of Agricultural Engineering, Division of Irrigation, Official Business.
Description.note: The St. Francis Dam was a 200-foot high concrete gravity-arch dam built between 1924 and 1926 in St. Francisquito Canyon (near present-day Castaic and Santa Clarita). The dam collapsed on March 12, 1928 at two and a half minutes before midnight. The resulting flood killed more than 600 residents plus an unknown number of itinerant farm workers camped in San Francisquito Canyon, making it the 2nd greatest loss of life in California after the 1906 San Francisco earthquake. It is considered the worst American civil engineering failure in the 20th century.|~|View of the outside wall of the largest remaining portion of the Saint Francis Dam after its collapse, known as the tombstone section.

Title: Letter on Hotel Brandon stationery accompanying photographs of weirs in the Fort Sumner area, 1940
Description.caption: [In pencil:] 3/18/1940. [In ink:] These are the pictures Arthur Morgan took of the control weirs in Ft. Sumner area. We'll your have printed what you want and 2 each for me as I would like to use in my progress report. Of course Warga [sp] will want the films back some time but no hurry as he has to account for them. [In pencil:] 10 prints. March 25 1940. Films attached H7B took 2 prints each of 5 to Carlsbad. [Stationary heading:] Dudley Yard, Owner - Manager, Member American Hotel Association, Texas Hotel Association, Official AAA Hotel, Hotel Brandon, Air Conditioned, "The Home on the Range," Pecos, Texas, Gateway of the Carlsbad Caverns and Big Bend Country.
Description.note: Arthur Morgan was the design engineer for the Miami Conservancy District flood control system and  the first chairman of Tennessee Valley Authority from 1933 until 1938.
